#Approach:

💡 IDEA
- Queue me FRONT element remove karna hota hai.
- Stack me sirf TOP remove kar sakte hain.
- Isliye s1 → s2 transfer karte hain.
- Transfer ke baad oldest element s2 ke top par aa jata hai.
- Usko pop karte hain aur remaining elements wapas s1 me daal dete hain.

⚙️ APPROACH
Push(x):
1. Direct s1 me push kar do.

Pop():
1. Agar s1 empty hai → return -1.
2. Saare elements s1 se s2 me transfer karo.
3. s2 ka top pop karo (ye queue ka front hoga).
4. Remaining elements s2 se wapas s1 me transfer karo.
5. Popped value return karo.

📝 EXAMPLE

Push(5)
Push(10)
Push(15)

s1:

Top
15
10
5

Pop()

Transfer s1 → s2

s2:

Top
5
10
15

Now:
pop() from s2 = 5

Remaining:

Top
10
15

Transfer back to s1

s1:

Top
15
10

Returned Answer = 5

Queue after pop = [10,15]

❓ WHY TWO STACKS
- First reversal:
  s1 → s2

- Oldest element top par aa jata hai.

- Second reversal:
  s2 → s1

- Original queue order preserve ho jata hai.

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Push : O(1)

Pop  : O(N)
       (Transfer twice)

Space: O(N)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- s1 stores queue elements.
- s1 → s2 transfer order reverse karta hai.
- s2 ka top = Queue Front.
- Pop ke baad elements wapas s1 me daalne padte hain because question specifically bolta hai final elements s1 me hone chahiye.
- Ye "Push Efficient, Pop Costly" implementation hai.

#Code:

import java.util.Stack;

class MyQueue {

    Stack<Integer> s1 = new Stack<Integer>();
    Stack<Integer> s2 = new Stack<Integer>();

    void Push(int x) {
        //You can code here
        s1.push(x);
    }

    int Pop() {
        //You can code here

        if(s2.isEmpty()){
          if(s1.isEmpty()){
            return -1;
          }
          while(!s1.isEmpty()){
            s2.push(s1.pop());
          }
        }
        int ans = s2.pop();

        //now pushing back all elements to s1 stack
        while(!s2.isEmpty()){
          s1.push(s2.pop());
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
